    {
      "prompt": "A series RC circuit is connected to a DC power supply of voltage V0. Initially, the capacitor in the circuit is uncharged and at 0V. After switching on the power supply, how long does it take for the voltage across the capacitor (VC) to reach approximately 63% of its final steady-state value? Explain your reasoning.",
      "answer": "It takes about RC time constant or roughly five time constants (\(5RC\)) for VC to reach around 63.2% of V0 in a series RC circuit after power is applied.\n\nReasoning: Capacitors charge according to \(V_c = V_0 (1 - e^{-t/RC})\) as t increases. After one RC time constant, the voltage reaches about 36.7% of V0; two constants reach ~63%, three ≈86%. Thus five constants represent around 95-98% which is typically rounded to 63% for practical approximation.",
      "rubric": [
        "- Correctly identify that it takes approximately RC time constant",
        "- Explain the charging equation \(V_c = V_0(1 - e^{-t/RC})\) and its implications",
