      "prompt": "In a DC circuit with an RC time constant of 2 seconds, what is the voltage across the capacitor after exactly one second? Show your work.",
      "answer": "After 1 second (which equals half of the RC time constant), the voltage across the capacitor will be \(V_c = V_0(1 - e^{-1/RC}) \approx 63\%\) of \(V_0\). Since we are at exactly one RC time constant, VC should be about 63.2% of its final value.\n\nCalculation: Using exponential decay formula \(V_c = V_0 (1 - e^{-t/RC})\), with t=1s and RC=2s, gives \(V_c ≈ 0.632 \cdot V_0\) or approximately one-third less than the supply voltage.",
      "rubric": [
        "- Calculate that after exactly one time constant VC = 63% of initial voltage",
        "- Show use of exponential decay formula with t/RC=1",
        "- Provide result (≈ 63.2\% V0) and explain significance"
      ],
      "skill": "apply"
